column30: DEFINITION
column31:
level 6 
Single Use Items, Sanitary Items and Fishing Gear according to the EU-Directive
Brackets ( ) mean not yet certain that this litter type is considered under the directive

column30: Plastic irrigation pipes from agriculture generated during construction, renovation, and demolition
Other plastic items from agriculture generated during  construction, renovation, and demolition

Plastic sheeting used to cover greenhouses generated during the construction, renovation, and demolition

This category is possibly only separable from other plastic sheeting by experienced workers
A foamed plastic tray in which seedlings are grown
A plastic container in which plants are grown.

column13: equipment for holding or protecting shellfish
column17: Plastic Mussels/oyster mesh bags,  net sack, socks
column30: A special bag or sack made out of extruded net which is used for growing (underwater) and packing mussels, oysters and other shellfish species. These bags can have different sizes and shapes e.g. sack-like and tubular and the mesh net can have different thicknesses.

column13: equipment for holding or protecting shellfish
column30: A special tray made out of square mesh used for growing oysters. Trays may be single, double or triple stacked, with or without feet, doors, v-braces and hooks.

column13: equipment for holding or protecting shellfish
column30: Pieces of plastic sheeting about 50X40 cm which are cut at one end into fringes or stripes so they look a little like a grass skirt from Hawaii. They are used to protect mussel cultures from animals that feed on mussels.
A light sandal made of plastic, with a thong between the big and second toe.

column21: Shoes and sandals made of artificial polymer materials - not flip-flops
column30: Items of footwear made of artificial polymers - not flip flops

Gloves used to do household chores such as dishwashing gardening, etc. They are typically made out of different polymers including latex, nitrile rubber, polyvinyl chloride. Less heavy-duty than industrial gloves.

Gloves specifically dedicated to industrial applications, mechanical, engineering, agriculture, fisheries and aquaculture and construction. They are typically made out of different polymers including latex, nitrile rubber, polyvinyl chloride and neoprene. More heavy-duty than household gloves.
A hard or padded protective hat, various types of which are worn by construction workers, workers from offshore installations, soldiers, police officers, motorcyclists, sports players, and others.

column17: plastic construction waste other than from agriculture
column30:
Plastic waste materials generated during the construction, renovation, and demolition of buildings or structures. These may include drainage pipes, waste pipes, plastic tubes for cables, , construction foam, etc.

Not foamed insulation materials
Plastic packaging (pouches, bags) and plastic containers suitable for storing, transporting, selling fishing baits.
Boxes made out of foamed polystyrene, which are used for packaging fish or other seafood.
Boxes made out of plastic materials (other than expanded polystyrene), which are used for packaging fish or other seafood.

A long nylon thread, usually attached to a baited hook, with a sinker or float, and used for catching fish. The fishing line may be found tangled or not and with or without hooks, sinkers  and floats.
An item attached to the top of some types of fishing nets, like seine and trammel that keeps them hanging vertically in the water. Floats come in different sizes and shapes.

Tangles of a blue, black or orange rope that are used to protect bottom trawling nets against wear and tear. A dolly rope consists of around 30 strings; each string has around 25 threads. The dolly rope string as well as the separated threads can occur in tangles in the marine environment. Tangles of dolly rope should consist entirely of dolly rope.

column21: Tangled nets and rope without dolly rope or mixed with dolly rope
column30: Tangled pieces of plastic open-meshed material made of twine, cord, or something similar, used typically for catching fish. They may be found tangled with rope or dolly rope.

column25: Nets and pieces of net < 50 cm
column30: Pieces of plastic open-meshed material made of twine, cord, or something similar, used typically for catching fish; smaller than 50 cm in the longest dimension.

column25: Nets and pieces of net > 50 cm
column30: Pieces of plastic open-meshed material made of twine, cord, or something similar, used typically for catching fish; bigger than 50 cm in the longest dimension.

column13: Other fishing related litter items (e.g. other than fish boxes, fishing line, nets, traps, pots, light sticks etc.)
column30: Other fishing related litter items that are not explicitly addressed by the fishing-related items included on this list e.g. soft and hard plastic baits such as wobblers, spinners etc.

Stationary plastic traps or pots used to catch crustaceans such as lobsters and crabs. Though the size and shape of the traps may vary, most feature a net covering and a cone-shaped entrance tunnel through which a crab or lobster is enticed with bait, but cannot escape from.

column13: Plastic Fishing light sticks / fishing glow sticks incl. packaging
column30: An item that is used by anglers in order to make baits more attractive to fish. Fishing light sticks or glow sticks are typically tubes filled with fluorescent fluid. They can be found in a variety of sizes.
Pots made of plastic or PVC tubing, weighted with concrete, and typically having a volume of 4 litres. Octopus seeking refuge in the pots can be trapped.

column21: String and filaments exclusively from Dolly ropes
column30: Strings and filaments from blue, black or orange string that are used to protect bottom trawling nets against wear and tear. A dolly rope consists of around 30 strings; each string has around 25 threads.

column21: Foamed polystyrene  cups and cup lids
column30: Single-use cups and their lids for coffee and other beverages; made out of  foamed polystyrene. They have a wide range of uses in restaurants, bakeries, or catering settings.
column36: perhaps as shown under cps_ as with paper

column30: Single-use cups and their lids for coffee and other beverages; made out of non-foamed artificial polymer materials. They have a wide range of uses in restaurants, bakeries, or catering settings.
column36: perhaps as shown under cps_ as with paper

column30: Single-use knives, forks, and spoons
Single-use plates and trays
Stirrers are used when serving hot drinks such as tea and coffee or other drinks such as cocktails
A drinking straw or drinking tube is a small pipe that allows its user to more conveniently consume a beverage.

A shotgun cartridge is a self-contained cartridge often loaded with multiple metallic "shot", which are small, generally spherical projectiles. The shells consist of a plastic tube mounted on a brass base holding a primer. Also plastic wads from shotgun cartridges can be found on their own.

column13: Other medical items (swabs, bandaging, adhesive plasters etc.)
column30:
Items deemed necessary for the treatment of an illness or injury. These may include swabs, bandaging, adhesive plasters, etc. 

Can be made of other materials than artificial polymers.

A wide variety of artificial polymer packages used for the packaging of the wide variety of pharmaceutical solids, liquids, and gasses. Some of the common primary plastic packages are: blister packs, small bottles and containers, tubes, ampoules, etc.

A plastic tube with a nozzle and piston or bulb for sucking in and ejecting liquid in a thin stream, used for cleaning wounds or body cavities, or fitted with a hollow needle for injecting or withdrawing fluids.

column21: Plastic mesh bags for vegetable, fruit and other products
column30: A special mesh bag made out of polypropylene, polyethylene or high-density polyethylene used for packaging and transporting agricultural products such as vegetables, fruit, bird feed etc.
A plastic bag used for picking up and removing the faeces of a dog or other pet.
Heavy duty sacks are plastic sacks typically designed to contain more than 25 Kgr of content such as animal feed, fertilizers, garden rubbish, etc.
Heavy-duty sacks and other containers used for packaging and shipping salt.

Shopping bags are medium-sized bags, typically around 10–20 litres in volume (though much larger versions exist, especially for non-grocery shopping), that are used by shoppers to carry home their purchases. Shopping bags can be made with a variety of plastics; polyethylene (LDPE, LLDPE, etc.) is the most common one. They usually have handles.
Small plastic bags refer to small-sized bags such as freezer bags, zip-lock re-sealable food bags, poly bags, etc.

column17: The part that remains from  tear-off plastic bags
column30: Plastic packing bags are commonly found on the market in packs of 10, 20, 50, etc. This litter item refers to the part that remains after tearing-off the bags.

column17: Body care and cosmetics bottles & containers
column21: Plastic beach use related body care and cosmetic bottles and containers
column30: Bottles and containers of body care and cosmetics products used at the beach such as sun cream, suntan or after sun lotion, etc.

column17: Body care and cosmetics bottles & containers
column21: Plastic Non-beach use related body care and cosmetic bottles and containers
column30: Bottles and containers of body care and cosmetics products  such as shampoo, shower gel, toothpaste, perfume and others that are not explicitly used at the beach.
Plastic bottles and containers with a volume of 0.5 litres or less, used to hold water, juice or other beverages for consumption.
Plastic bottles and containers with a volume larger than 0.5 litres, used to hold water, juice or other beverages for consumption.

column25: Plastic Engine oil bottles & containers <50 cm
column30: Plastic bottles and containers smaller than 50 cm in any dimension, used for packaging motor oil, engine oil, or engine lubricant.

column25: Plastic Engine oil bottles & containers >50 cm
column30: Plastic bottles and containers bigger than 50 cm in any dimension, used for packaging motor oil, engine oil, or engine lubricant.

column21: Food containers made of hard non-foamed plastic
column30: Plastic containers used for carrying or storing food, such as fast food containers, Tupperware, lunchboxes, etc.  Made of non-foamed plastic

column21: Food containers made of foamed polystyrene
column30: Foamed polystyrene containers used for carrying or storing food, such as fast food containers, lunchboxes, etc.
Other plastic bottles and containers such as drums (cylindrical containers) generally used for the transportation and storage of liquids and powders.

column17: Plastic bottles and containers of cleaning products
column30: Bottles and containers of cleaning products such as detergents, toilet cleaners, glass cleaners, etc.
Large plastic flat-sided containers with a handle used for storing or transporting liquids, typically petrol or water.
A cartridge made out of plastic for devices that are used to inject grease, silicone, or other fluids.
Small plastic discs (and their keep cases) on which sound and data can be stored.

Large plastic packaging or sheeting used for the protection or covering/wrapping of large cargo objects. Plastic sheeting is used for a variety of industrial and commercial applications. It comes in many sizes, strengths, styles, and colours depending on the application.

Plastic food packets and wrappers created and designed in various colours, materials, shapes, sizes and styles for crisp food products (i.e. potato chips, etc.) or sweets (i.e. chocolates, candy, ice-creams, etc.).
A plastic stick attached to the bottom of a popsicle/lolly/ice-cream or lollypop used as a handle to facilitate the eating process.
Four or six pack rings or yokes are a set of connected plastic rings that are used in multi-packs of beverages, particularly of beverage cans, to hold the cans together
Plastic caps and lids from bottles and containers of cleaning products (i.e. detergents, toilet cleaners, glass cleaners, etc.) and chemicals.
Plastic caps and lids from bottles and containers, used to hold water, juice or other beverages for consumption.
Plastic caps and lids from unidentified bottles and containers.

Plastic structures around the circumference (usually) of the closure that is often found attached below a closure in bottles, jars, and tubs. The bottom part of a cap that breaks off when the cap is screwed off.
Plastic containers typically used to transport or store different types of items and products, other than fisheries and aquaculture related.
Plastic bands and straps used for fastening any type of package. Polypropylene and polyester strapping is the most commonly used plastic strapping on the market. Usually made of quite hard plastic.

A short stick with a small amount of cotton on each end that is used for cleaning, especially the ears. The cotton is usually no-longer attached. The ends are rough when touched, where the cotton was attached. This feature can be used to separate from lolly sticks.

column13: Other personal hygiene and care items
column30:
Other identifiable personal hygiene and care items that do not fit in any other category of this list. 

Can be made of other materials than artificial polymers.
Basic garments for infants consisting of absorbent synthetic polymer material drawn up between the legs and fastened about the waist, used to retain urine and faeces.

column13: Sanitary towels/panty liners/backing strips, Tampons and tampon applicators
column30: Absorbent pads worn by women to absorb menstrual blood.

column13: Sanitary towels/panty liners/backing strips, Tampons and tampon applicators
column30: A feminine hygiene product designed to absorb the menstrual flow or a plug of material used to stop a wound or block an opening in the body and absorb blood or secretions. The tampon applicator should be recorded within this category.
Toilet bowl fresheners, which are attached inside the toilet bowl to keep it smelling fresh.
A small disposable synthetic cloth treated with a cleansing agent, used especially for personal hygiene.

column13: Fin trees (from fins for scuba diving)
column30: The plastic supports placed inside diving flippers or fins to keep them in shape.
The plastic remains of fireworks such as caps of rockets, covers for fuses, exploding parts of battery fireworks.

Any plastic object that children play with, as well as objects commonly used at parties. Party poppers are small devices used as an amusement at parties, which explode when a string is pulled, ejecting thin paper streamers.

column13: Biomass holder from sewage treatment plants and aquaculture
column30: Plastic Filter Media or Biofiltration Media are small (1-4 cm diameter ca. 1 cm high) usually round plastic items that look a bit like a cake. https://www.bing.com/images/search?q=Plastic+Filter+Media+or+Biofiltration+Media&FORM=HDRSC2
Plastic cushions (such as foam rubber) placed between a boat and a dock or between two boats to lessen shock and prevent chafing.
A stout cord of strands of plastic fibres twisted or braided together, with a diameter larger than 1 cm.
column36: changed level 2 from unidentified to shipping related

column30: Small objects that produce a flame, commonly used for lighting cigarettes or cigars.

column13: Tobacco pouches / plastic cigarette box packaging
column30: Plastic containers (pouches, boxes) used for cigarettes and tobacco.

column13: Tobacco products with filters (cigarette butts with filters)
column30: A cigarette filter, also known as a filter tip, is a component of a cigarette, placed at the one tip of the cigarette in order to absorb vapours and accumulate particulate smoke components. The filter is commonly made from synthetic plastic cellulose.
Items made of fibreglass, a common type of fibre-reinforced plastic using glass fibre. Examples of fibreglass items include water pipes, pods, domes, traffic lights, etc.
Floating devices that serve as navigation marks, marking reefs or other hazards, mooring locations, fishing gear. They can be anchored (stationary) or allowed to drift with ocean currents.

column13: foamed plastic items and fragments not made of foamed polystyrene
column17: other foamed plastic items and fragments not made of foamed polystyrene
column30: Items and fragments (other than packaging or insulation related) made out of foamed sponge-like plastic, such as mattresses, bathing sponges, etc.

column13: foamed plastic items and fragments not made of foamed polystyrene
column17: Foamed plastic used for packaging and/or insulation
column30: Lightweight cellular foam (mainly foamed PU and PE materials ) used especially for insulation (i.e. in walls, roofs, and foundations as thermal insulation and water barrier) or as a packing material.
Fragments of plastic that are smaller than 2.5 cm in the longest dimension and originate from unidentifiable plastic non-foamed polystyrene items.
Fragments of foamed polystyrene that are smaller than 2.5 cm in the longest dimension and originate from unidentifiable polystyrene items.
Fragments of plastic that are larger than 50 cm in the longest dimension and originate from unidentifiable plastic non-foamed polystyrene items.
Fragments of foamed polystyrene that are bigger than 50 cm in the longest dimension and originate from unidentifiable polystyrene items.
column33:
FP04
foamed plastic (insulation & packaging)
FP05
foamed plastic other

column30: Fragments of plastic that are bigger than 2.5 cm and smaller than 50 cm in the longest dimension and originate from unidentifiable plastic non-foamed polystyrene items.
Fragments of foamed polystyrene that are bigger than 2.5 cm and smaller than 50 cm in the longest dimension and originate from unidentifiable polystyrene items.
column33:
FP04
foamed plastic (insulation & packaging)
FP05
foamed plastic other

column21: Items that are made of  non-foamed plastic, which are identifiable but do not fit in any other litter type category in this list.
column30: Items that are made of non-foamed artificial polymers, which are identifiable but do not fit in any other litter type category in this list.

column21: Items that are made of  foamed polystyrene, which are identifiable but do not fit in any other litter type category in this list.
column30: Items that are made of foamed polystyrene, which are identifiable but do not fit in any other litter type category in this list.

column21: String and cord (diameter less than 1cm) not from dolly ropes or unidentified
column30: A material consisting of threads made of plastic twisted together to form a thin length, with a diameter smaller than 1 cm; excluding string and cord from dolly ropes.
A roughly cylindrical open container with a handle made of plastic and used to hold and carry liquids.

A cable tie (also known as a wire tie, hose tie, steggel tie, zap strap or zip tie, and by the brand names Ty-Rap and Panduit strap) is a type of fastener, for holding items together, primarily electrical cables or wires.
Plastic items used for untangling or arranging the hair, as well as plastic glasses tinted to protect the eyes from sunlight or glare.

Different sorts of plastic adhesive tape: used in painting, to cover areas on which paint is not wanted (masking tape); strong cloth-backed waterproof adhesive tape (duct tape); box-sealing tape, parcel tape or packing tape used for closing or sealing corrugated fibreboard boxes.

A brush used for painting, typically consisting of bristles fastened into a wooden or plastic handle. 

Can be made of other materials than artificial polymers.
Any writing or drawing utensils made predominately from artificial polymer materials.
Plastic tags used to mark fish and shellfish such as lobsters and plastic cargo seals (pull-tight) both usually with a serial number.
Mobile phone devices and any other type of telephones.
Plastic cone-shaped objects that are used to separate off or close sections of a road.

A circular object that revolves on an axle and is fixed below a vehicle or other object to enable it to move easily over the ground. 

Can be made of other materials than artificial polymers.
Any part of a car or other transport vehicle (i.e. boat) made of artificial polymer materials and fibre glass.
Any type of clothes and garments made of artificial polymer materials.
Various types of footwear such as shoes and sandals made of leather and/or textile.
Sacks and other packaging items made of a strong, coarse fabric from hemp or jute (Hessian).
Textile receptacles with an opening at the top, shoulder straps or a handle, used for carrying things.
Other textile items, including pieces of cloth, rags, etc. that are unidentifiable, as well as other identifiable cloth textile items, which do not fit in any other category of this list.
Thick woven fabric used for covering the floor or other fabric used for furniture, fittings, and other decorative house accessories such as curtains.
A heavy durable cloth made of cotton, hemp, or jute, used for sails, tents, etc.
Any glass and ceramic material which is used for construction purposes such as brick, roof tiles, floor tiles, bricks, cement, etc.
Pots made of pottery, weighted with concrete, and typically having a volume of 4 litres. Octopus seeking refuge in the pots can be trapped.
Glass or ceramic dishes or dishware used for serving food and dining,, plates, cups, glassware, serving dishes and other useful items for practical as well as decorative purposes.
Glass or ceramic containers with a narrow neck, used for storing drinks or other liquids. Includes pieces of glass that can be identified as coming from a bottle.
Wide-mouthed cylindrical containers made of glass or pottery, especially used for storing food. Includes pieces of glass that can be identified as coming from a jar.
Other identifiable ceramic items, which do not fit in any other category of this list.
Other identifiable glass items, which do not fit in any other category of this list.
Fragments of pottery or glass items that cannot be identified.

column13: Light bulbs and fluorescent light tubes
column30: A low-pressure mercury-vapour gas-discharge lamp that uses fluorescence to produce visible light.

column13: Light bulbs and fluorescent light tubes
column30: A glass bulb inserted into a lamp or a socket in a ceiling, which provides light by passing an electric current through a filament or a pocket of inert gas. Includes all types, also halogen, LED etc.
A thick metal wire or a group of wires usually inside a rubber or plastic covering, which is used to carry electricity or electronic signals.

Fishing related items such as: weights/sinkers (a metal weight used in conjunction with a fishing lure or hook to increase its rate of sink, anchoring ability, and/or casting distance); lures (any bright artificial bait consisting of metal mounted with hooks and trimmed with feathers)
A portable trap that traps lobsters or crayfish. It can be constructed of wire or metal and netting. An opening permits the lobster or crab to enter a tunnel of netting.
Metal dishes or dishware used for serving food and dining, including cutlery, plates, cups, serving dishes and other useful items.
Metal resulting from the disuse of metal products such as parts of vehicles, building supplies, and surplus materials.

column17: Bottle caps, lids & pull tabs from cans
column30: Metallic caps and lids from bottles and containers, including the pull tabs from cans.

A type of dispensing system which creates an aerosol mist of liquid particles; used with a can or bottle that contains a payload and propellant under pressure. Indicative examples of such items are: spray paints, cleaning spray foam, engine oil spray, room odour spray, etc.
Metal containers that are used for storing and selling e.g. beer, or soft drinks.
Metal containers that are used for storing and selling food such as beans, soup, fish, corn, etc.
Other metal containers that are used for storing and selling products that are not food or beverages or paints.
Metal containers that are used for paint.
Large cylindrical metal containers used for storing or shipping bulk cargo, i.e. oil, chemicals, etc.
Thin aluminium sheeting or leaves used especially to cover and wrap food.
A single-use barbecue grill made from a lightweight aluminium material.
Other identifiable metal items that are smaller than 50 cm in the longest dimension and do not fit in any other items category of this list.
Other identifiable metal items that are bigger than 50 cm in the longest dimension and do not fit in any other items category of this list.

A metal mesh woven, knitted, welded, expanded, photo-chemically etched or electroformed steel or other (wire mesh); A metal wire with or without clusters of short, sharp spikes set at short intervals along it, used to make fences or in warfare as an obstruction (barbed and plain wire).

Metallic (mostly electrical) devices or pieces of equipment designed to perform a specific task such as air conditioners, dishwashers, clothes dryers, freezers, refrigerators, kitchen stoves, water heaters, washing machines, trash compactors, microwave ovens, etc.
Small-sized batteries that are typically used in small electronic devices such as flashlights, cameras, etc.
Any part of a car or other transport vehicle (i.e. boat) made predominantly of metal, including vehicle batteries.

column13: Cups, food  trays, food  wrappers,  drink containers
column30: Cups for coffee and other beverages; made out of cardboard. They have a wide range of uses in restaurants, bakeries, or catering settings.

column13: Cups, food trays, food  wrappers,  drink containers
column17: Food  trays, food wrappers, drink containers
column30: Single-use food trays, food wrappers and drink containers, made out of paper.
A thick, stiff paper that is used to make boxes and models.
Containers made out of carton with a plastic-lining used for food products, other than milk.
Containers made out of carton with a plastic-lining used for milk.
A small bag made of paper, commonly used as shopping bags, packaging, etc.
A short paper stick with a small amount of cotton on each end that is used for cleaning, especially the ears.

column13: Tubes and other pieces of fireworks
column30: Small paper/cardboard containers/tubes filled with explosive chemicals that produce bright coloured light patterns or loud noises when they explode (fireworks).
A rectangular container made of paperboard, used as packaging for cigarettes. It may also include a plastic covering.
Fragments of paper items that cannot be identified.
Other identifiable paper and cardboard items, which do not fit in any other category of this list.
Printed publications consisting of paper sheets and containing news, articles, advertisements.
Stationary wooden traps used to catch crustaceans such as lobsters and crabs. Usually covered in a net.
Boxes made out of wood, which are used for storing or transferring fish or other seafood.

column13: Ice-cream sticks, chip forks, chopsticks, toothpicks
column30: Various wooden sticks, including sticks from ice-creams, small wooden forks from fast food suppliers (chip forks), tapered sticks of wood held together in one hand and used as eating utensils in Asian cousine (chopsticks), short pointed pieces of wood used for removing bits of food lodged between the teeth (toothpicks).
A bottle stopper made of cork or a similar material. Note that plastic corks should be recorded under plastic caps and lids.
Wooden containers typically used to transport or store different types of items and products. Not fish boxes!
column33:
WD04
Processed timber and pallet crates

column30: A flat wooden structure that heavy goods are put onto so that they can be moved using a fork-lift truck.

A small thin piece of wood or cardboard tipped with flammable chemicals that catch fire with friction (match); a small container filled with explosive chemicals that produce bright coloured patterns or loud noises when they explode (fireworks).
Other identifiable wooden items smaller than 50 cm in the longest dimension, which do not fit in any other category of this list, e.g. planks, boards, beams.
Other identifiable wooden items larger than 50 cm in the longest dimension, which do not fit in any other category of this list, e.g. planks, boards, beams.
A tall boot that is made out of rubber and that keeps the feet and lower legs dry.
A thin rubber sheath, used during sexual intercourse as a contraceptive or as a protection against infection. Within this category also the packaging should be recorded.

A small coloured rubber sack-like object which is inflated with air and then sealed at the neck, used as a child's toy or a decoration. Within this category any balloon ribbons, strings, plastic valves and balloon sticks that are or were attached to balloons should be recorded.
A spherical toy ball, usually fairly small, made of elastic material which allows it to bounce against hard surfaces.
Other identifiable rubber pieces, which do not fit in any other category of this list.
A thin, flexible loop that is made of rubber and used to hold things together.
An inflatable usually ring-shaped rubber tube designed for use inside a pneumatic tire.

Rubber sheeting made of rubber (or rubber-like artificial polymer). Rubber sheets are used for varied purposes e.g. flooring, under shower pans, drainage systems, as lining for water containers and in construction.

A rubber covering, typically inflated or surrounding an inflated inner tube, placed round a wheel to form a soft contact with the road (tyre); a continuous rubber band of material used in machinery for transferring motion from one wheel to another (belt).

column17: Grease (only to be included after proof through chemical analysis)
column30: lubricating grease

column17: oil & tar (only to be included after proof through chemical analysis)
column21: Oil (only to be included after proof through chemical analysis)
column30: all types of oil usually found as viscous droplets or mats e.g. on a beach. This is usually the sludge that remains after centrifuging heavy fuel oil before use as fuel by ships. It can also be crude oil, from loss of cargo, as well as hydraulic oil.

column17: oil & tar (only to be included after proof through chemical analysis)
column21: Tar (only to be included after proof through chemical analysis)
column30: tar is the name for any oil that has been in the marine environment for such a length of time that the more volatile components have evaporated - usually more dry than oil, but there is a smooth transition between oil and tar

column17: Other generally dark-coloured oil-like chemicals (only to be included after proof through chemical analysis)
column30: Other generally dark-coloured oil-like chemicals includes e.g. Tall oil, also called "liquid rosin"

column17: unidentified generally dark-coloured oil-like chemicals i.e. no chemical analysis carried out
column30: unidentified generally dark-coloured oil-like chemicals

column17: other generally light-coloured paraffin-like chemicals (only to be included after proof through chemical analysis)
column30: other generally light-coloured paraffin-like chemicals e.g. ethylene-oligomeres

column17: Paraffin Wax (only to be included after proof through chemical analysis)
column30: All types of paraffin wax, refined or less refined. "Paraffin" and "wax" are often used as synonyms for paraffin wax! Paraﬃn wax is always a mixture of n-alkanes and, depending on the degree of purity, various secondary components, which can vary greatly in their composition. It is by no means a sharply deﬁned composition of hydrocarbons. There is no one paraﬃn wax!

column17: unidentified generally light-coloured paraffin-like chemicals i.e. no chemical analysis carried out
column30: Unidentified generally light-coloured paraffin-like chemicals

column17: Vegetable oil (only to be included after proof through chemical analysis)
column30: Vegetable oil, such as palm oil

column17: unidentified chemicals i.e. no chemical analysis carried out
column30: any unidentified chemicals
all types of non-packaged food and food remains
